n from the violence and injustices brought on by civil war, capitalist exploitation, racism, and the failures of the state. In fleshing out the experiences, theologies, and innovations of black women Pentecostals, the contributors show how Pentecostal belief and its various practices reflect the movement's complexity, reach, and adaptability to specific cultural and political formations.Contributors. Paula Aymer, John Burdick, Judith Casselberry, Deidre Helen Crumbley, Elizabeth McAlister, Laura Premack, Elizabeth A. Pritchard, Jane Soothill, Linda van de Kamp  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aPentecostal churches. 0aPentecostalism. 0aWomen, BlackxReligious life. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Pentecostal & Charismatic.2bisacsh1 aCasselberry, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPritchard, Elizabeth A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002116zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002116423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002116.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles